She was also eccentric in some ways.  There was a lunch party given by the Constituency for the local MP, and all planned in advance and so on, and about five days before the lunch was due, he was arrested \endash  the MP was arrested \endash  for peein
g down an area railings in Westminster at two o\rquote 
clock in the morning, and fined two shillings and sixpence at Bow Street. Whereupon he applied for the Chiltern Hundreds, resigned from all his Clubs and everything, but still wanted to come to the lunch. So 
the Chairman of the South West Herts. Conservatives said to my mother, \'93You must be very careful not to mention this latest event, because he\rquote s very embarrassed by it\'94
.  Well, she was sitting next to him throughout the lunch, and noticed that things were getting frosty, but she couldn\rquote 
t work out why.  The reason that they were getting frosty was that she was enlisting his support to get a by-law through Parliament \endash  which you had to do in those days, I think \endash anyway, getting a Regulation or a by-law or a la
w, penalising owners of dogs which fouled the footpath!  (LAUGHS)  And she just had this - had a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11542699  very \'85 very unpleasant lunch!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12328331\charrsid12328331 She once (COUGHS) with a boy who came in from \'85 he was the son of the cleaner who came in to do the house, and he was saving up to buy a motorbike \endash 
 he was about 15 or 16 \endash  he used to come in on Saturdays and earn a few quid from tidying up the weeds and things, and he got a bike, and on the day after his 16}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid12328331\charrsid12328331 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12328331\charrsid12328331 
 birthday, he went off on a ride, and came off it, and lost a leg. His mother was completely devastated, totally devastated, as you can imagine. So my mother \endash  which I think was a very reasonable thing to do \endash  thought, \'93Well, she needs 
\'85\'94 and the boy was 16 or 17 and resilient, and knew how to cope with things, or thought that he knew how to cope with things, but the mother couldn\rquote t stop weeping and worrying and so on. So my mother thought, well, \'93
She had better talk to people who had lost a leg\'94, and she arranged a dinner party of people with one leg. Which I think was intellig
ent and clever.  But she forgot to tell them what it was all about!  So the first one arrived, and this was in the 1950s, so there were quite a lot of people who were war veterans, who were limbless one way or another. But she ended up with five couples c
oming, and all the men had one leg.  And then the boy and his mother.  Eventually, they said, \'93What the hell is going on?  Are you pulling our legs?\'94
  (LAUGHS)  And she explained.  And then it was absolutely fantastic, because they all started talking about
 the lore of having a wooden leg and stumps, and talcum powder, and the best kind of leather for the harness, and so on and so on and so on.  And then, after a few drinks, they talked about how having one leg missing, in fact made their sex lives very int
eresting!  So the poor mother of the boy perked up, but the boy\rquote s mother was also quite reassured that all was not finished, and that he would survive.  
