ivided into between males. In the town, in the older parts of the town, neighbourhoods were woman-centred, so that if you have a daughter, and as she approaches marriageable age, you had a storey on the top of your house for her and her husband, or two st
oreys if you\rquote ve got two daughters, or you buy the house next door, or whatever.  The neighbourhoods become matri-focal, and men move from neighbourhood to neighbourhood, i.e. you go and live in your father-in-law\rquote s house, which he\rquote 
s built for his daughter.
