\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12328331\charrsid12328331 The Zuwaya used to be transhumant people with land up in the north coastal plain by Ajdabiya and gardens in the oases, and what they did \endash 
 the bulk of the population \endash  was to move between the two. They would cultivate grain in the north, where there was rain \endash  if there was any rain \endash 
 and the gardens with the date palms mostly, in the south, with about eight hundred miles between them. So they did this annual movement to and fro, and while they were making this movement, the young adventurous and exp
loratory young men would go off into Black Africa and trade - no doubt, in earlier times, slaves, but also camels, and goods which you could only get in the Sudan \endash 
 certain kinds of scented wood and things of that kind - which they then brought up to the North.  And so there was a trade in transhumance from as far back as one can find any kin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8661703 d of historical record at all.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12328331\charrsid12328331 
Then the Italians arrived, and tried to stop the annual movement, and the population became divided.  Large numbers of people went into exile in Chad and Niger and Sudan. One phase of the history I\rquote 
ve missed out, was with the Sahusya, which is a religious revival movement begun by King Idris\rquote s grandfather, so that there were lodges of the Sahusya throughout the Sahel and throughout Libya, 
